          awardPiece: "breastplate_of_righteousness",
          reading: "The Edict of Milan in 313 AD transforms Christianity's status from persecuted sect to legally protected religion. Constantine, having experienced a vision before the Battle of Milvian Bridge, becomes Christianity's first imperial patron. He moves the capital from Rome to Byzantium, renaming it Constantinople—'the City of Constantine'—which becomes the 'New Rome,' a Christian capital adorned with magnificent churches and sacred relics.\n\nYet legal protection brings new challenges: theological disputes that were once internal matters now threaten imperial unity. The most explosive controversy concerns Arius, a presbyter from Alexandria who teaches that the Son is a created being, subordinate to the Father. This denies Christ's full divinity and shakes the Church's foundations. Constantine convenes the First Ecumenical Council at Nicaea in 325 AD, bringing together 318 bishops from across the Christian world.\n\nAt Nicaea, the bishops—many bearing scars from persecution—proclaim the Nicene Creed: the Son is 'of one essence' (homoousios) with the Father, begotten not made, true God from true God. St. Athanasius of Alexandria, though young, emerges as orthodoxy's champion, spending decades in exile defending this truth. His famous declaration rings through history: 'God became man so that man might become god' (theosis)—the Orthodox understanding of salvation as participation in divine life.\n\nThe Second Ecumenical Council at Constantinople in 381 AD addresses confusion about the Holy Spirit, affirming His full divinity and procession from the Father. The Nicene-Constantinopolitan Creed, still recited in Orthodox liturgy today, takes its final form. The Cappadocian Fathers—Basil the Great, Gregory of Nazianzus, and Gregory of Nyssa—provide sophisticated Trinitarian theology, distinguishing between God's one essence (ousia) and three persons (hypostases).\n\nChristological controversies dominate the next centuries. The Third Ecumenical Council at Ephesus in 431 AD confronts Nestorius, who appears to divide Christ into two persons. The Council affirms Mary as Theotokos (God-bearer), not merely Christotokos (Christ-bearer), because she bore not just a man but God incarnate. This isn't Marian speculation but Christological precision.\n\nChalcedon in 451 AD faces the opposite error: Eutyches claims Christ has only one nature, with His humanity absorbed into divinity. The Council proclaims Christ as one person (hypostasis) in two natures (divine and human), unmixed, unchanged, undivided, inseparable. This delicate balance preserves both Christ's full divinity and full humanity, essential for salvation—what is not assumed is not healed.\n\nIconoclasm erupts in the 8th century when Byzantine emperors, influenced by Islamic rejection of images and seeking military success, ban sacred icons. For decades, iconographers are persecuted, monasteries destroyed, and beautiful mosaics whitewashed. St. John of Damascus, safe in Muslim-controlled Damascus, writes brilliant defenses: since Christ took flesh, He can be depicted; icons are windows into heaven, not idols. The Seventh Ecumenical Council at Nicaea in 787 affirms icon veneration (not worship), distinguishing between latreia (worship due to God alone) and proskynesis (honor shown to holy persons and objects). The Triumph of Orthodoxy in 843 finally restores icons permanently, celebrated annually on the first Sunday of Lent.",
